elements.2211.03114_dda13f8073606937de6c179596d73: The homogenisation of the fracture toughness is considered in the context of a propagating hydraulic fracture
elements.2211.03114_da4f8d9b3e63d12515467242215bf: The radial (penny-shape) model is utilized, in order to incorporate the impact of the viscosity-toughness regime transition over time
elements.2211.03114_05c90edb6ae017e9eb720e1cfacac: A homogenisation strategy based upon temporal-averaging is investigated
elements.2211.03114_ad46e77e61d9f5fa0718a87f4cbec: This approach incorporates the instantaneous fracture velocity, meaning that it should remain effective in the case of step-wise crack advancement
elements.2211.03114_f4e6b4f280cd4b62d241fac1c0ceb: The effectiveness of the approach is demonstrated for periodic toughness distributions, including those which are unbalanced, utilizing a highly accurate solver.
elements.2211.03114_313ae953e8938c72eafdebea4ca98: Hydraulic fracturing (HF) driven by pressurised fluid is a phenomenon observed in many natural and industrial processes
elements.2211.03114_88320e15e485c86395abf598dc163: For example, natural processes of fluid fracturing due to the magma and volcanic gas flow are well known (see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_f985989bf5325579b6f45ce07d619: The hydraulic fracturing phenomenon also occurs in medicine during fluid injection in human tissue or fluid-driven rupture of articular cartilage associated with osteoarthritis or hypertension
elements.2211.03114_52d1283eef6e000fe8c96a64c8cc5: The latter receives significant attention from both medical practitioners and modellers, due to the significant health and social issues associated with aortic dissection
elements.2211.03114_59681c9c849d9e647f5f5cb118df5: Prediction of fluid driven fracture evolution is also an important step in the design and safety assessment of many technological applications and industrial processes
elements.2211.03114_6e54c292c6d3795e2fbba640e2277: One highly relevant technological application related to environmental issues is CO2 sequestration (capturing and storing of atmospheric CO2 in underground reservoirs)
elements.2211.03114_0f954d6732fb72a9598e289f69725: Here, assessment of possible fracturing of the storage reservoir due to the CO2 injection must be performed during the design stages to ensure it maintain its integrity
elements.2211.03114_60ae8355781d3302d83ec99aa8c07: A similar technological process where fluid driven hydraulic fracturing is often used is in the stimulated extraction of hydrocarbons from low porosity reservoir rock which would otherwise be economically unviable (for overviews, see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_17dbf9b129cb3728d8292c1a2da3b: There are many design variables defining successful hydraulic fracturing (HF), such as achieved production, fracture geometry and the effective stimulated reservoir volume
elements.2211.03114_f8893dd363b51b2115307a8403bfa: The tight/low permeability unconventional reservoirs encountered during hydraulic fracturing are characterised by highly complex structures, due to the depositional history and subsequent deformation related to the tectonic movement, glaciation, and other factors
elements.2211.03114_4fb686a395623dbc6619cd9c8fc92: This heterogeneity can be observed in all of the processes described above
elements.2211.03114_53b658621a8097c03bfb48acf7444: For example, the reservoir properties can be measured by core-logs and production data at almost every scale exhibition strong heterogeneity; the aortic wall segment comprises several layers of intima/media and adventitia with various material properties
elements.2211.03114_736425bca11b268d9ae453cc14596: When predicting process of HF evolution using computational methods it is clear, however, that it is neither time or cost-effective for computational models of hydraulic fracturing to incorporate this level of detail, and some upscaling techniques are almost always used
elements.2211.03114_3fc5b3fe875fa2d3be0b33434289e: This problem of homogenising material parameters is far from unique to hydraulic fracture
elements.2211.03114_4aa83740ff2ca2224a26f2e2e72e7: Effective homogenisation strategies for the various properties of composites (for instance elastic, thermal, electrical etc.) are well developed and often have rigorous physical justifications (see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_09ef4c595b24df0cacd8f11b1223b: A number of formulas and procedures to evaluate the average composite properties have been proposed using a variety of approaches
elements.2211.03114_33715e6590edcd8e6f9a7affe836c: Importantly, while most provide slightly different results, these all lie within the Hashin-Strickman bounds
elements.2211.03114_26704e5ae29bb3d1a70bb1805d86f: In practice, many approaches are developed to ensure the results of both the original system and homogenised approximation are identical for a specific type of loading
elements.2211.03114_51df056155024e4112162ec2c02d4: Away from this type of loading, it is hoped (or demonstrated) that they will provide an acceptable approximation
elements.2211.03114_f3501c0db20c413aaff9b3896e22f: Unfortunately it is well known, as documented by Kachanov and his colleagues (see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_ac927aca55ea851f592f2e4f14018: ), that homogenisation of the fracture toughness does not make physical sense, at least in the case of microfractures
elements.2211.03114_8ad40822a488ed53f2343c6889378: On the other hand, this issue is increasingly recognised as crucial for successful HF practice, as heterogeneous (mostly laminated) underground structures with varied toughness are always present
elements.2211.03114_d78bd8a5bde2499ca6fbc468121e0: Any homogenisation strategies for dealing with this also have the constraint that solvers incorporating them must be able to provide data in real-time to be effectively utilized by practitioners
elements.2211.03114_cd450f019bde3c734424b079c4710: It is still not clear how to simultaneously homogenise the elastic properties while also homogenising the fracture toughness (see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_14515aa0aba001559209f93f864d1: This raises the question: is it possible to build a consistent homogenisation theory for the fracture toughness that is able to predict the resulting crack growth in real-time and with an acceptable level of accuracy, at least for a very restricted class of practical problems and processes? If one knows that such a homogenisation is not possible then, for a specific type of composites under predefined loading conditions, can some approximate averaging be developed that can provide practitioners with acceptable results (for some specific settings)? Moreover, if this is achieved for a small number of optimal (in some sense) solutions, is it possible to verify those few solutions in more detail by computing the problems and process solutions considering the materials microstructure? While the answers to these questions are extremely important to the practice of hydraulic fracture, as has been documented by many researchers (see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_776b2c19e300e21473a16cb901be5: , in general up to this point a naÃ¯ve averaging has been implemented to approximate the toughness (moving averages, averages on one computational cell, etc) without any guarantee on the accuracy of the results obtained
elements.2211.03114_959d2f2dc4e02fdadf5a9986d5cd6: Recently, concentrated attempts have been made address a notion the averaged toughness in the case of the fluid driven fracture
elements.2211.03114_63d99204fc51ddb1494e90c218aba: A phenomenological and well-balanced approach used in
elements.2211.03114_c3dbf1adaf36d859ad11443dbf470: allowed a simple formula for the averaged toughness to be proposed for the case of a step-wise toughness distribution
elements.2211.03114_bcefcf591be54953c1fbebe787323: This has since been extended to the development of an algorithm for computing the fracture evolution within a domain including inhomogeneity of the toughness, in-situ stress and fluid leak-off for a plane strain crack
elements.2211.03114_85ac45eac9ae452531085e504c334: this approach was verified showing when the results become acceptable from the practical point of view, not only for periodic stepwise but also for sinusoidal toughness distribution, by using a very accurate plane strain (KGD) solver
elements.2211.03114_e3dd085073cc3291d625749581623: When providing such analysis/comparison, the most difficult aspect is simulating the process in the required level of details concerning the material microstructure
elements.2211.03114_2f5a9cf4f1a6a9b36d325eb2b76a8: In the case of HF, the total fracture length can be hundreds of meters, while some of the process data available is the scale of several centimetres
elements.2211.03114_7a06e3291cd16c4144bdd142ebceb: The aim of this paper is to extend the approach proven be efficient for the plane strain case with periodic toughness to the radial inhomogeneity
elements.2211.03114_dae962da23922b4ad80ee7058c76a: Even though such toughness heterogeneity can be considered as an exceptionally rare case (although not impossible, such as fractures in wood (tree rings), stone, or arterial walls, see Fig.
elements.2211.03114_7c1db53ccccf9e20fccd021cbf84a: ), the aim in this instance is to prove the concept rather than to claim a specific problem is solved
elements.2211.03114_8e7ab59331b7a3fb0096e9405a912: Moreover, as the approach proposed in this paper and in the plane strain case is based upon the concept of (temporal) averaging, rather than the maximum toughness assumption, it can be used for a wider class of composites and heterogeneity distributions (not only periodic, but also the random toughness distributions)
elements.2211.03114_a43c98dba5c487afbb20f02b390c5: Crucially, the measure used to define the homogenised toughness also incorporates the instantaneous crack velocity
elements.2211.03114_ac5db946bbdeda5e4b19174cc0292: , meaning that it should remain effective even during the step-wise crack extension observed in HF (see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_45e64edfbcd643ae080e7a20bb114: and references therein), or when there is also inhomogeneity of the in-situ stress, fluid leak-off or other parameters.
elements.2211.03114_130d8ee791638d54555ce1c8d28cd: This work is organised as follows
elements.2211.03114_48718981185f54b4f8448b349490e: First, the problem of radial hydraulic fracture with inhomogeneous toughness is formulated, with the model, description of the toughness distribution, method of parameterising the fracture regime, and numerical solver all outlined
elements.2211.03114_3b299fb6a70acbaa3f5517ae02294: In the next section, the differing homogenisation strategies for the toughness are proposed, and a thorough investigation conducted for the cases where the toughness distribution is balanced, unbalanced, or has only a minimally thick layer of high-toughness
elements.2211.03114_92158a9b9d555210364dd2f74fb0f: A summary of results is then provided at the end.

elements.2211.03114_8f7b8a70c2511d33a867576d5f2a2: A variety of homogenisation strategies for the material toughness have been considered, in the context of hydraulic fracture (HF) of rock with a periodic toughness distribution
elements.2211.03114_afa4370e77e9d6bd7b18ede31f86c: The strategies considered took two different forms
elements.2211.03114_3390d4b0251e7d93d185df29d27d1: The first was the maximum toughness strategy proposed in
elements.2211.03114_b1e483ca92162abaa210dd801c7a0: , while the second utilized the concept of temporal-averaging previously proposed by the authors
elements.2211.03114_ddb84cd3df8aa993e6a590376fa7b: A wide range of periodic toughness distributions were considered, including differing fracture regimes, unbalanced material distributions, and taking both step-wise and sinusoidal forms
elements.2211.03114_efae252d8a545cb561c28f8a28250: The investigation was able to demonstrate the following:
elements.2211.03114_91e9f8b7319d78cc2c7c73e34c791: The temporal-averaging approach to homogenising the fracture toughness was consistently more effective than the maximum toughness strategy for the radial model of hydraulic fracture (as has previously been demonstrated for plane strain HF
elements.2211.03114_03f5d53c6b037ccce7c0861b3c930: The largest difference between the two was seen for a fracture starting in the transient-viscosity dominated regime, while that for the toughness-toughness distribution was far smaller (see Figs.
elements.2211.03114_9439c2a2f6b16d19eaf429df2b591: The effectiveness of both measures improved with time (after the first 2-3 toughness periods) for the toughness-toughness and toughness-transient distributions, but not for the transient-viscosity distribution
elements.2211.03114_66b759fe7015e6d83e8ed1ef37b5c: Here, the transition from the viscosity to transient distribution caused an increase in the relative error of key process parameters for the maximum toughness strategy, while the temporal-averaging approach remained more consistent.
elements.2211.03114_3c253152090f1b6e234b3a445a722: The results above also hold for the case with unbalanced layering, where the maximum toughness layer only makes up a small portion of the material
elements.2211.03114_d4df6664e31a635ac55a68ee6bbcd: The likely physical explanation for this was outlined in Sect.
elements.2211.03114_20af15d921d0f867a30ae162117a2: It was demonstrated that even in the case of an extreme imbalance (
elements.2211.03114_12223fa8dbe336327eaa7dc08e865: ), the only effect was a small increase in the relative error of the approximation, with the maximum toughness strategy more adversely affected than the temporal-averaging approach
elements.2211.03114_ee13021be0946afaf39de48c26e16: It is however unlikely that these result would hold if the maximum toughness material instead made up the majority of the heteogeneous body (
elements.2211.03114_43347926a8a7da7fc5556d92ab139: Interestingly, in the case with an extremely unbalanced layering of the rock strata, it was still the transition between viscosity and toughness dominated regimes which played the crucial role in determining the effectiveness of the homogenisation method
elements.2211.03114_e01304bbac6c472f3e4cb51c492c7: As such, the only significant effect of unbalanced layering on the homogenisation methods was through it's influence on the fracture evolution (for cracks with one layer starting in the viscosity dominated regime).
elements.2211.03114_521c66604976023faef408d00703a: It should be restated that the temporal averaging homogenisation strategy utilized in this work is not dependent upon the periodic distributions examined here, and should continue to be effective for disordered toughness distributions as well
elements.2211.03114_c822ef5ab77999226e7c390581e58: One factor of the presented analysis that should be highlighted is that the principles behind the toughness homogenisation strategy outlined here are not particular to the hydraulic fracture process
elements.2211.03114_75830c3f76e87367848444bc1b432: This means that they should continue to provide an effective homogenisation strategy for any steady state propagation process within a heterogeneous media
elements.2211.03114_e6da35d6f4737637bf49add248e01: While these results indicate the effectiveness of the temporal averaging homogenisation strategy for a system only experiencing toughness heterogeneity, there are a number of crucial effects which should still be considered for HF

elements.2211.03114_8ffd68bedfbe88835277d44368a85: Additionally, the step-wise fracture advancement present even in homogeneous media (see e.g.
elements.2211.03114_2e2b6e7608e30478403f02c98dd66: ) could have an even larger impact when coupled with the effect of toughness heterogeneity
elements.2211.03114_3e97d4611bda2a71175118b9d6022: The fact that the utilized measures
elements.2211.03114_a7e13f373834edb70bccbe6a7b253: , is however promising in this regard
elements.2211.03114_05df785056d86288b31c21527c154: The dependence on the instantaneous velocity does however lead to the most significant open question regarding the proposed strategy
elements.2211.03114_9646bf75ff5ce36962b9002f8dc81: For this work, the results of existing numerical simulations were used to provide the instantaneous velocity used to compute the average toughness
